THE RISK (context, do not rewrite): perturbation [{"nodeId":"seg.enterprise","op":"set","value":0.21,"note":"GPU-pod increment (~1/4 of the enterprise slice) carries no discrete PDU content; legacy refresh continues its documented decline"}], likelihood 0.24, category model-structure

FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "The only growing part of the enterprise 29% ships as pre-integrated GPU racks with shelf power — the venture addresses only the shrinking remainder",
 "narrative": "seg.enterprise (0.29) looks like the conservative, PDU-sticky base: on-prem halls refreshing rack power on slow cycles. But Synergy is explicit that enterprise capacity was flat for years and is only now growing again 'thanks to GenAI applications and GPU infrastructure' — and that increment arrives as OEM-integrated GPU pods built to vendor reference designs with in-rack power shelves, not as field-installed PDUs. Meanwhile the legacy stock the PDU thesis actually addresses is the part Synergy shows declining two percentage points a year toward 19% by 2031. The model books the whole 0.29 as PDU-addressable; structurally, only the shrinking half is.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Synergy: after a sustained period of no growth, on-premise capacity is getting a boost from GenAI/GPU infrastructure — the enterprise segment's growth is exclusively AI-density capacity",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c20",
    "digest:seg-mix#c2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Enterprise AI capacity is procured as pre-integrated racks (vendor reference designs with busbar/power-shelf distribution) from OEMs, bypassing the discrete rack-PDU purchase entirely; the residual PDU-buying legacy stock is the component falling ~2pp/year toward 19% share by 2031",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c22",
    "digest:seg-mix#c5"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "seg.enterprise 0.29 is a single-source capacity share with no sensitivityRange and no decomposition into legacy-refresh vs GPU-pod capacity; treating all of it as PDU-addressable overstates the enterprise slice a new PDU entrant can sell into during Year 1",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:seg.enterprise",
    "digest:seg-mix#c3"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The enterprise share is the model's most 'boring' number — a declining legacy segment nobody expects surprises from. The trap is that its headline share is being propped up by exactly the capacity type (GPU pods) that doesn't buy the product, so the stable-looking 0.29 conceals a faster-shrinking addressable core.",
 "falsifier": "CE enterprise DC refresh data (e.g., a Vertiv/Schneider channel survey or distributor sell-through) showing intelligent rack PDUs attached to new enterprise AI/GPU deployments at rates comparable to general-purpose IT racks.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "Synergy's GenAI-boost claim and the 2pp/yr on-prem decline are both sourced; the open question is what fraction of CE enterprise AI capacity ships pre-integrated vs stick-built — documented for US hyperscale-adjacent deployments, thinner evidence for mid-size European enterprises. [evidence revision: The trigger (GenAI-driven enterprise growth) is confirmed, but the critical bypass mechanism is undercut: NVIDIA's flagship enterprise reference architecture explicitly ships in a traditional-rack-PDU variant (three 2U PDUs per rack), and multiple PDU market analysts attribute demand growth directly to AI/GPU density. Busbar/power-shelf pods exist but coexist with PDU-based AI racks rather than universally displacing them, weakening the claim that the whole growing increment is non-PDU-addressable. Lowered from 0.35 toward the contradicting evidence, but not to the floor since the legacy-vs-pod decomposition gap and the busbar option remain real.]"
}

